Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient + data service — one instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance each time they're requested
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — new instance each time they're navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`; shared state (caches, auth tokens) should live once. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation gets fresh state — no stale data leaking between visits. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reason; each detail screen should start clean. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the transient ViewModels; avoids binding to a stale VM. |

**Key rule of thumb:** never inject a transient into a singleton — the transient effectively becomes a singleton too. Here the dependency flows downward (`Page → ViewModel → DataService`), from transient to singleton, which is safe.

> If you later need to cache a page for performance (e.g., a heavy dashboard), promote both the page **and** its ViewModel to `AddSingleton` together so their lifetimes stay aligned.
